This is a textbook example of "coverage without verification." Every production method is called, so coverage reports 95%+, but almost nothing is actually **asserted**. Here's the severity-ranked audit:

---

## 🔴 Critical — Assert-Free Tests (coverage-touching, zero verification)

These tests exercise code paths but prove nothing. Any regression passes green.

**1. `AddProduct_Works` (line 17)** — Calls `AddProduct` but never verifies the product was stored.
```csharp
// Fix: verify the product is retrievable
_catalog.AddProduct(product);
var stored = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNotNull(stored);
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", stored.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, stored.Price);
```

**2. `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 32)** — Calls `UpdatePrice` but never checks the price changed.
```csharp
// Fix: assert the new price
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated!.Price);
```

**3. `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 38)** — Calls `RemoveProduct` but never checks the product is gone.
```csharp
// Fix: assert the product no longer exists
_catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
```

**4. `GetProductCount_Works` (line 63)** — Calls `GetProductCount` on an **empty** catalog and discards the result. No assert at all.
```csharp
// Fix: add a product, then assert count
_catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
var count = _catalog.GetProductCount();
Assert.AreEqual(1, count);
```

**5. `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (line 68)** — Applies a 10% discount but never checks any price was reduced. A bug in the discount formula (e.g. `1 + fraction` instead of `1 - fraction`) would pass.
```csharp
// Fix: assert discounted prices
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);
Assert.AreEqual(8.991m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001")!.Price);
Assert.AreEqual(17.991m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-002")!.Price);
```

**6. `ImportFromCsv_Works` (line 84)** — Imports CSV but never verifies the product was created.
```csharp
// Fix: verify the imported product
_catalog.ImportFromCsv("SKU-001,Widget,9.99");
var imported = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNotNull(imported);
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", imported.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, imported.Price);
```

---

## 🟠 High — Weak Assertions (assert exists, but proves nothing useful)

**7. `GetProduct_Works` (line 23)** — Asserts `IsNotNull` but never checks the returned values. A bug returning the wrong product passes.
